    "summary": "The construction of the Forbidden City (1406–1420 AD) in Beijing by the [[event:100|Ming Dynasty]] Yongle Emperor created the world's largest palace complex and one of the most perfectly preserved examples of traditional Chinese palatial architecture, serving as the ceremonial and political center of Chinese imperial government for nearly five centuries (1420–1912). The Yongle Emperor, who had seized the throne from his nephew in a civil war and moved the capital from Nanjing to Beijing to be closer to the northern frontier, employed an estimated million workers and 100,000 craftsmen to construct a complex of 980 buildings covering 72 hectares.\n\nThe Forbidden City's design embodied Chinese cosmological principles: aligned precisely on the north-south axis, with the emperor's throne at the symbolic center of the universe, every architectural detail expressing the cosmic order that the emperor mediated between Heaven and humanity. The outer court's three great ceremonial halls — used for audiences, state ceremonies, and major festivals — represented the public face of imperial power; the inner court's residential palaces were the private domain of the emperor, his consorts, concubines, and eunuch household staff. Only the emperor, the imperial family, and authorized officials and servants could enter — hence the name 'Forbidden City.' The complex is now the most-visited museum in the world (the Palace Museum), and its extraordinary state of preservation, including over 9,000 rooms and vast collections of imperial art and artifacts, makes it one of the greatest cultural heritage sites in human history.",
